text-text-muted leading-relaxed","children":"Early in your loan term, the majority of your payment goes to the lender as interest. As the balance drops, the interest charge is calculated on a smaller amount, allowing more of your payment to chip away at the principal balance."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"bg-primary/5 p-8 rounded-2xl border border-primary/10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-3xl font-semibold text-text-primary mb-6","children":"How Extra Payments Affect Your Amortization"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-6","children":"Even small extra payments made early in the loan can have a massive impact. Because interest is compounded, every dollar of principal you pay off early is a dollar that you won't have to pay interest on for the remaining years of the loan."}],["$","div",null,{"className":"grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"bg-background p-6 rounded-xl border border-border","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2","children":"Shorten Your Loan Term"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-text-muted","children":"Consistent extra principal payments can shave years off a 30-year mortgage, helping you reach the \"debt-free\" milestone much sooner."}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"bg-background p-6 rounded-xl border border-border","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2","children":"Maximize Interest Savings"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-text-muted","children":"Reducing the principal balance faster significantly lowers the total interest paid to the bank, keeping more money in your pocket."}]]}]]}]]}],["$","section",null,{"children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-3xl font-semibold text-text-primary mb-6","children":"The Benefit of Bi-Weekly Payments"}],"$L3"]}]]}],"$L4"]}],["$L5","$L6"],"$L7"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-muted leading-relaxed","children":"A popular strategy is to make half of your mortgage payment every two weeks. Resulting in 26 half-payments (or 13 full payments) per year, this simple trick can reduce a 30-year mortgage by about 4 to 6 years depending on your interest rate. Use our amortization calculator to see how different payout frequencies impact your long-term savings."}]
